{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17597749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17597749"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:28:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:28:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15426"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15426"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0,0.71,0,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8117"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65931"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8117"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15426"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51377"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8760"},{"type":"tags","id":"10075"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19687"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22028"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65931"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA pathologist is examining a gallbladder specimen following cholecystectomy (Image). The mucosal surface shows numerous yellow deposits against a red background, giving it a speckled appearance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this mucosal appearance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute inflammatory infiltrates","Adenomyomatous hyperplasia","Cholesterol deposits in the mucosal wall","Rokitansky-Aschoff sinuses","Xanthogranulomatous inflammation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe description matches cholesterolosis, commonly known as strawberry gallbladder. \u003Cstrong\u003ECholesterol deposits\u003C/strong\u003E accumulate within macrophages in the lamina propria of the gallbladder mucosa, appearing as yellow spots against the red background of the mucosa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute inflammatory infiltrates\u003C/strong\u003E would show a more uniform appearance with possible exudates. \u003Cstrong\u003EAdenomyomatous hyperplasia\u003C/strong\u003E involves muscle hypertrophy and epithelial invagination. \u003Cstrong\u003EXanthogranulomatous inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E shows yellow-brown nodules extending into the wall. \u003Cstrong\u003ERokitansky-Aschoff sinuses\u003C/strong\u003E are epithelial invaginations into the gallbladder wall that do not cause a strawberry appearance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Strawberry gallbladder (cholesterolosis) is characterised by cholesterol deposits in the gallbladder mucosa giving a red-yellow speckled appearance.","Cholesterolosis is a benign condition that may be associated with cholesterol gallstones but does not typically cause symptoms."],"references":["Di Ciaula A, Wang DQ, Portincasa P. An update on the pathogenesis of cholesterol gallstone disease. Curr Opin Gastroenterol. 2018 Mar;34(2):71-80. doi: 10.1097/MOG.0000000000000423. PMID: 29283909; PMCID: PMC8118137","Chen Y, Kong J, Wu S. Cholesterol gallstone disease: focusing on the role of gallbladder. Lab Invest. 2015 Feb;95(2):124-31. doi: 10.1038/labinvest.2014.140. Epub 2014 Dec 15. PMID: 25502177","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51377"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15426"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21255"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21255"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9q54LYjGokvCtBLl6yqFhOpZ7EV8qQ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/9q54LYjGokvCtBLl6yqFhOpZ7EV8qQ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":502,"height":327}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51377"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T17:26:17+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T17:26:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8117"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65931"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":n